	<div class="posts">
	<a name="83993626">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://eclipse.org/">Eclipse.org Main Page</a>.  And it's IBM once again, this time with a little help from some friends and the Eclipse project.  The Eclipse BOF is Tuesday night, while I am in Italian class, so there's nothing to do for it unless I go to the reception afterwards just to say hello to Gregor Kiczales and find out about his new business.  There's a CD with Eclipse 2.0.1 builds for the usual suspects.  I am fascinated by Eclipse, but every time I start to follow their news lists, I see how deep in the bowels of things they are and stand back and wait.  By now it should be stabilizing and it would be good to see how well it holds up.  One thing I appreciated about this open-source effort is that, although highly Java-centric, it is friendly to the plaftorm it is built for, and the Windows versions are COM friendly and also Windows UI consistent.  I think they did the right thing in how they handled UI libraries to achieve platform integration.  And one of these days I may actually install it.  The disk is nice and I am coming to appreciate the OSI certified lable on releases.<br>
